{
  "doc_id": "10150",
  "text": "Given an undirected graph, the Feedback Vertex Set (FVS) problem asks for a minimum set of vertices such that after removing this set, the resulting graph has no cycle. This problem arises in a variety of applications, including deadlock resolution, circuit testing, artificial intelligence, and analysis of manufacturing processes [CITATION_1] . Because of its importance, the FVS problem has been studied for a long time in the algorithm area. It is one of Karp's 21 original NP-Complete problems [CITATION_2] and is proved to be NP-hard even in planar graphs [CITATION_3] . The current best approximation ratio for the FVS problem in general graphs is 2 due to Becker and Geiger [CITATION_4] and Bafna, Berman and Fujito [CITATION_5] .",
